Public Responses to Jihadist Terrorism on Social Media

Migration and Societal Change, Utrecht University

Christian S. Czymara

20 Jun 2025

Introduction

  • Social media shapes how societies respond to terrorist attacks
    • Emotional expression and political discourse (Bove et al.Â 2024; Hurtado Bodell & Menshikova 2024)
    • Increases in both hate speech (Czymara & Gorodzeisky 2024; Kaakinen et al.Â 2018) and solidarity (Garcia & RimÃ© 2019)
    • Offline effects: Far-right voting (Giavazzi et al.Â 2023), hate crimes (MÃ¼ller & Schwarz 2021)
  • Research question: How do immigration-related discussions evolve on Twitter after Jihadist attacks?

Terror Management Theory

  • Fear of death leads people to defend cultural worldviews (Greenberg et al., 1986; Yum & Schenck-Hamlin 2005; Fischer-PreÃler et al., 2019)
  • After terrorist attacks, reactions include:
    • Religious behavior, nationalism, prejudice/stereotyping
    • Counterbigotry activism, altruism, appreciation of helpers
  • Focus of this study on reactions relating to migration or intergroup relations

Topic Expectations: Nationalism & Prejudice

  • Group threat theory: majorities may view minorities as threats after âsignificant eventsâ (Blumer, 1958)
  • Jihadist terror attacks can trigger exclusionary views (Legewie, 2013)
  • TMT categories:
    • Prejudice/stereotyping: Negative outgroup sentiment
    • Nationalism/patriotism: Positive ingroup sentiment

Topic Expectations: Prosocial Behavior & Counterbigotry

  • Reactions to terror attacks can also include empathy, tolerance, and solidarity
  • Shared trauma can strengthen intergroup bonds (social resilience) (Garcia & RimÃ©, 2019)
  • TMT categories:
    • Prosocial behavior: Empathy, emotional support
    • Counterbigotry activism: Calls for tolerance, rejection of hate

The Dynamic Nature of Topics

  • Online reactions to terrorism shift over time
    • Hate speech and negative emotions peak early, then decline (Czymara & Gorodzeisky, 2024; Garcia & RimÃ©, 2019)
    • Solidarity and opinion-driven content emerge later (Fischer-PreÃler et al., 2019)
  • Nationalism and prejudice are expected to peak early, followed by a rise in prosocial behavior and counterbigotry

Search string

  • Identify Tweets that deal with migration related topics, including Muslims (much debated migrant group), but no direct search for insults or derogatory terms, nor attack specific hashtags
  • Language-specific search string, English version (all accessible at osf.io/zdt5b):
 [1] "migration"   "immigration" "migrant"     "immigrant"   "foreigner"  
 [6] "migrants"    "immigrants"  "foreigners"  "refugee"     "refugees"   
[11] "asylum"      "islam"       "islamist"    "islamism"    "muslim"     
[16] "muslims"     "salafist"    "Salafism"    "jihad"
  • Accounts located in the city of each attack took place

Distribution of Tweets

  • 102173 Tweets posted by 36390 accounts

Method

Keyword-Assisted Topic Modelling

  • keyATM (Eshima et al., 2024) is a semi-supervised model using predefined keywords (identifying both expected and unexpected topics)
  • Uses keywords to initialize the model, which then refines the topics based on the data
  • Reduces subjectivity by directly targeting theoretical concepts
  • Less sensitive to topic number specification

Topic Identification

  • Focus on TMT reactions tied to intergroup dynamics:
    • Nationalism: National pride, anti-immigrant sentiment
    • Prejudice: Stereotypes of minorities as violent or threatening
    • Counterbigotry: Rejection of hate, emphasis on tolerance and solidarity
    • Prosocial: Empathy and support for victims and affected communities

Keywords

  • Keywords selected based on prior research and empirical validation

Final Model

  • Lowercasing, stemming, removing stopwords, top 15 most frequent terms per language, @mentions, punctuation, numbers, symbols, URLs
  • Covariate keyATM to examine temporal variation: Dummy predictor (first 2 days vs.Â days 3â7)
  • In addition to 4 keyword-based topics, 20 non-keyword topics estimated
  • Separate models for each language

Validation

  • Annotated 150 most representative Tweets for each topic-language combination (based document-topic distribution \(\theta\))
  • Zero-shot classification with GPT-3.5-turbo-0125 with manually validation
  • On average, each topic overlapped 70 percent with the GPT classification
    • 49 percent (Nationalism in English, Prosocial in French)
    • 89 percent (Prejudice in French and German)

Summing up

Conclusion

  • Terrorist attacks can trigger both exclusion and solidarity online
  • Nationalism peaked shortly after attacks, inclusionary topics gained prominence over time
  • Social media reveals shifts not easily captured in survey data
  • Limitations
    • Hate speech likely underrepresented due to platform deletions
    • Xâs changing user base (e.g.Â after Muskâs takeover) likely limits generalizability
